The paper deals with reinforcement learning (RL) agents and their training on web-based tasks, which are typically semi-structured and require a combination of natural language processing and computer vision. This suggests that the paper could belong to several arXiv CS sub-categories, including Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI), Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC), Machine Learning (cs.LG), Computational Linguistics (cs.CL), and Information Retrieval (cs.IR). Of these, cs.AI is the most likely category, as it encompasses a broad range of topics related to intelligent agents and their learning algorithms. However, cs.HC is also a strong possibility, given the focus on web interfaces and the need to design RL agents that can interact with humans in a natural and intuitive way. The other categories are less likely, but still plausible, as they relate to specific aspects of the paper's methodology, such as the use of neural networks (cs.LG), natural language processing (cs.CL), and information retrieval (cs.IR).
